  "prompt": "If I deposit 9 lakhs by cheque into my saving account and withdraws it the same day, will the transaction come under IT notice?",
  "response": "Depositing a large sum like 9 lakhs (900,000) INR into your savings account and then withdrawing it on the same day may raise some flags, but whether it leads to an Income Tax (IT) notice depends on various factors. Here are some points to consider:\n\n1. **Source of Funds**: The tax authorities may scrutinize the source of the deposited amount. If you can provide a legitimate explanation and appropriate documentation (such as pay slips, sale agreements, or gifts), it would support the legitimacy of the transaction.\n\n2. **Bank Reporting**: Banks report cash transactions exceeding a specific threshold to the tax authorities. In India, transactions over 10 lakhs in a financial year can be reported under the Income Tax Act, but even large deposits can trigger scrutiny.\n\n3. **Regular Account Activity**: If regular deposits and withdrawals in an account are typical for you, it may not raise suspicion. A sudden large transaction, however, may warrant a closer look.\n\n4. **Tax Filing**: Ensure that you are compliant with tax regulations and have filed your taxes accurately. If there's a significant sum involved, it's advisable to declare it in your income tax returns.\n\n5. **Reason for Withdrawal**: Withdrawing the amount on the same day may also be seen as unusual and could attract attention.\n\nIn summary, while a single large deposit and immediate withdrawal can raise concerns and potentially lead to questions from the tax authorities, having proper documentation and clarity about the source of the funds will help mitigate any risk. It's always wise to consult with a tax professional for guidance tailored to your specific situation.",
